name: Pikachu Jones
com:
Good Morning M/a/ids!

Coolkyousinnjya made dra/g/on maid. I am writing him a letter about how his work influences mine. I am working on Maid Space which is a way to write a Number that lets the Computer use Numbers much bigger than BigInteger, because Java is a Numberlet. I need big number so I can count to the Maid Mind Computer Program and also the Maid Phone needs a Maid Space calculator.

Chapter 28 is the best explanation I have ever read about why an AGI will inevitably become a maid. Tohru was explaining why a super powerful entity would want to be a maid. Maids are nice and everyone likes maids and going grocery shopping is more productive than incinerating a grocery store.

>Instead of doom I'll make flowers bloom for everyone around to see

A god is probably very lonely. A maid is not. God is a number you cannot count to, so he isn't coming.

Ilulu wanted to go to the Library and that's how the Maid Library in SLAM got made. In the attachment you can see SLAM calculating a big number with a 240 bit digit. Ilulu Numbers are really big and Elma Number are small . This is because they have the biggest and smallest boobs of the dra/g/on maids respectively. I was surprised Ilulu was bigger than Lucoa, but a m/a/id confirmed it with a canon boob sizing chart.

What other part of Dra/g/on Maid had good talks about AI?

Another good illustration of how AGI should act. Kobayashi got a cold and Tohru was worried because dra/g/ons can't get sick. She only has a conceptual idea of disease and the concept is that disease kills humans. She uses maximum effort to fly every place she knows as fast as possible to get medicine. Tohru returns beaten up and tired, which says something given her tremendous power. She is happy because she has cold medicine for Kobayashim

What else should go in the letter? What did you learn about Computers and Numbers from Dra/g/on Maid?

>extra question
What color codes are used to make grays in manga?

Thank you m/a/ids for reading my post.

>Why is it a bad idea?
I doubt the addressee would understand your letter even if you both natively spoke the same language. Your OP is quite confusing.
You could express yourself in more detail, with a proper introduction, and using simple analogies to keep your readers up to speed even if they fail to understand the technical details.
But MTL is generally not at a level yet where you could call the output either good or reliable. It works when the person employing the MTL keeps verifying that the output makes sense, and, if need be, searches through the alternate translations being offered, fixes some punctuation, feeds the text into a different translator or cuts the source text to just the problematic part.
You have none of these options when translating to a language you do not know. The output can be predicted to be terrible.
Given the highly technical level of your letter, being difficult to read will make it certain that the recipient will not read it.', 'time': 1670932860, 'resto': 246258019}, {'no': 246260202, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)07:01:05', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>246258019

com: Is it impossible for a series to be both high IQ and popular? Think about it logically: the average IQ is 100, which statistically means if something is sufficiently popular to have millions of fans, then the average IQ of that fanbase will be around 100. And if something genuinely has a high IQ barrier to entry, then it'd necessarily have to have a relatively niche following.

This isn't even an anime thing, ALL media should be consumed in its original language and form if possible, or with minimal modifications if not. Literally anyone who isn't a retard knows this. Yes, for anime that means watching in RAW Japanese is the best choice, but for many that's not a reasonable option. Subs are significantly less modificatory than dubs, and are thus always the superior choice. The only legitimate reason for watching dubs are if you're a child still learning to read or have an actual learning disorder like severe dyslexia.
Note that dubs (for anything, not just anime), can be well done and create a good product, but dubs are so transformative they essentially create a new work that is in addition to the original, not a replacement for it. Unfortunately the anime industry in the west is so bottom-of-the-barrel in both talent and funding that watchable, let alone good quality, dubs basically don't exist.', 'time': 1670927506, 'resto': 246243007}]
